t-content"><p>&#8220;But capitalism is just an economic system where the provision of goods, services, and labor is determined by individuals negotiating with each other, rather than by a centralized state authority.&#8221;</p><p>No, it&#8217;s not. That&#8217;s free markets. Capitalism is an economic system where private investment (capital) is the dominant form of investment in the production and distribution of goods and services, and is a system in which ownership can be separated from the management of such capital.</p></div><div class="reply"></div></div><ol class="children"><li class="comment byuser odd alt depth-2 parent " id="comment-7758333" data-sort-time="1555446229"><div id="div-comment-7758333" class="comment-body"><div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><div class="comment-author vcard"> <cite class="fn"><strong>TripK</strong></cite></div> <a href="https://reason.com/2019/04/16/are-socialists-more-like-libertarians-than-wed-like-to-admit/#comment-7758333">April.16.2019 at 4:23 pm </a></div><div class="comment-content"><p>No, it&#8217;s not. That&#8217;s your definition of Capitalism. Capitalism is an economic system characterized by private or corporate ownership of capital goods, by investments that are determined by private decision, and by prices, production, and the distribution of goods that are determined mainly by competition in a free market.</p></div><div class="reply"></div></div><ol class="children"><li class="comment byuser even depth-3 parent " id="comment-7759187" data-sort-time="1555521924"><div id="div-comment-7759187" class="comment-body"><div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><div class="comment-author vcard"> <cite class="fn"><strong>Mike</strong></cite></div> <a href="https://reason.com/2019/04/16/are-socialists-more-like-libertarians-than-wed-like-to-admit/#comment-7759187">April.17.2019 at 1:25 pm </a></div><div class="comment-content"><p>Translated for those who haven&#8217;t seen how this works out in reality:</p><p>&#8220