logy often sounds the same. These areas of &#8220;freedom&#8221; give Socialism&#8217;s victims the belief they have SOME control over their lives (hint: they really don&#8217;t &#8211; where it counts). Socialists don&#8217;t like American national defense (armed forces, etc.) &#8211; same with most Libertarians (and Anarchists), whose non-aggression principle goes too far and denies the right to and value of self-defense. Open immigration is a value to both groups. Not surprising then, is it, that someone in an afternoon conference, not looking too closely (you know, there are those &#8220;&#8230;professionally political, earnest kids, disheveled academics, and&#8230;feuding factions and squabbling cliques&#8221;) would see some similarities between Socialism and Libertarianism?</p></div><div class="reply"></div></div><ol class="children"><li class="comment byuser odd alt depth-2 parent " id="comment-7758491" data-sort-time="1555451784"><div id="div-comment-7758491" class="comment-body"><div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><div class="comment-author vcard"> <cite class="fn"><strong>ThomasD</strong></cite></div> <a href="https://reason.com/2019/04/16/are-socialists-more-like-libertarians-than-wed-like-to-admit/#comment-7758491">April.16.2019 at 5:56 pm </a></div><div class="comment-content"><p>Socialists do not believe in a single freedom. They do offer many permissions though, and the occasional license.</p></div><div class="reply"></div></div><ol class="children"><li class="comment byuser even depth-3 parent " id="comment-7758574" data-sort-time="1555458187"><div id="div-comment-7758574" class="comment-body"><div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><div class="comment-author vcard"> <cite class="fn"><strong><a href='http://themistoclesgrow.blogspot.com' rel='external nofollow ugc' class='url'>Zeb</a></strong></cite></div> <a href="https://reason.com/2019/04/16/are-socialists-more-like-libertarians-than-wed-like-to-admit/#comment-7758574">April.16.2019 at 7:43 pm </a></div><div class="comment-content"><p>Or they don&#8217;t even believe in freedom as a possibility.<br /> Not sure if that&#8217;s what you meant.</p></div><div class="reply"></div></div><ol class="children"><li class="comment byuser odd alt depth-4" id="comment-7760066" data-sort-time="1555593533"><div id="div-comment-7760066" class="comment-body"><div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><div class="comment-author vcard"> <cite class="fn"><strong>ThomasD</strong></cite></div> <a href="https://reason.com/2019/04/16/are-socialists-more-like-libertarians-than-wed-like-to-admit/#comment-7760066">April.18.2019 at 9:18 am </a></div><div class="comment-content"><p>Yes. That principle is baked into their philosophical cake. But put in the abstract it is often glossed over (much like their absolute reliance on compulsion) so I prefer to get people thinking in the specific before introducing that concept.</p></div><div class="reply"></div></div></li></ol></li></ol></li><li class="comment byuser even depth-2" id="comment-7759086" data-sort-time="1555516687"><div id="div-comment-7759086" class="comment-body"><div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><div class="comment-author vcard"> <cite class="fn"><strong>Ron</strong></cite></div> <a href="https://reason.com/2019/04/16/are-socialists-more-like-libertarians-than-wed-like-to-admit/#comment-7759086">April.17.2019 at 11:58 am </a></div><div class="comment-content"><p>Socialism is for open borders only in that it helps control the populace.</p></div><div class="reply"></div></div></li><li class="comment byuser odd alt depth-2" id="comment-7759184" data-sort-time="1555521834"><div id="div-comment-7759184" class="comment-body"><div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><div class="comment-author vcard"> <cite class="fn"><strong><a href='http://libertariantranslator.com' rel='external nofollow ugc' class='url'>Hank Phillips</a></strong></cite></div> <a href="https://reason.com/2019/04/16/are-socialists-more-like-libertarians-than-wed-like-to-admit/#comment-7759184">April.17.2019 at 1:23 pm </a></div><div class="comment-content"><p>BL should look at old newspapers. Anarchist means exactly the same as communist. The difference is that an anarchist was actually caught shooting or bombing someone. Aside from that they are the exact same thing&#8211;a thing Congress prohibited by law from entering These States.</p></div><div class="reply"></div></div></li></ol></li><li class="comment byuser even thread-even depth-1 parent " id="comment-7758361" data-sort-time="1555447226"><div id="div-comment-7758361" class="comment-body"><div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><div class="comment-author vcard"> <cite class="fn"><strong>mpercy</strong></cite></div> <a href="https://reason.com/2019/04/16/are-socialists-more-like-libertarians-than-wed-like-to-admit/#comment-7758361">April.16.2019 at 4:40 pm </a></div><div class="comment-content"><p>No. A thousand times no.<br /> Any resemblance is purely coincidental.</p></div><div class="reply"></div></div><ol class="children"><li class="comment byuser odd alt depth-2" id="comment-7759192" data-sort-time="1555522095"><div id="div-comment-7759192" class="comment-body"><div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><div class="comment-author vcard"> <cite class="fn"><strong>Mike</strong></cite></div> <a href="https://reason.com/2019/04/16/are-socialists-more-like-libertarians-than-wed-like-to-admit/#comment-7759192">April.17.2019 at 1:28 pm </a></div><div class="comment-content"><p>Said by someone who doesn&#8217;t know the history of where the term &#8220;Libertarian&#8221; originally came from. Here&#8217;s a link in case you want to trace back beyond Rothbard and the 1970&#8217;s US: <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Libertarianism" rel="nofollow ugc">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Libertarianism</a></p></div><div class="reply"></div></div></li></ol></li><li class="comment byuser even thread-odd thread-alt depth-1 parent " id="comment-7758364" data-sort-time="1555447301"><div id="div-comment-7758364" class="comment-body"><div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><div class="comment-author vcard"> <cite class="fn"><strong><a href='http://theWideNet.blogspot.com' rel='external nofollow ugc' class='url'>Diane Reynolds (Paul.)</a></strong></cite></div> <a href="https://reason.com/2019/04/16/are-socialists-more-like-libertarians-than-wed-like-to-admit/#comment-7758364">April.16.2019 at 4:41 pm </a></div><div class="comment-content"><p>There are in fact strains of marxism which intersect with libertarianism, and there&#8217;s even a term &#8220;Libertarian Marxist&#8221; which seems to get people&#8217;s hackles up around here, but when you understand the ideas behind the term, it makes some sense. The REAL Marxism (you know, that one that no one has ever tried?) the state is supposed to fade away leaving only a voluntary collective of individuals who base their society on mutual aid. The structures are supposed to be entirely non-coercive and decisions are totally democratic. I&#8217;m not going to rehash here why that idea always goes sideways and you end up with gulags and Stalin, but on paper, there certainly are some shared points with regular libertarians.</p></div><div class="reply"></div></div><ol class="children"><li class="comment byuser odd alt depth-2" id="comment-7758492" data-sort-time="1555451880"><div id="div-comment-7758492" class="comment-body"><div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><div class="comment-author vcard"> <cite class="fn"><strong>ThomasD</strong></cite></div> <a href="https://reason.com/2019/04/16/are-socialists-more-like-libertarians-than-wed-like-to-admit/#comment-7758492">April.16.2019 at 5:58 pm </a></div><div class="comment-content"><p>I agree, the ideal of Marxism is compatible with much of libertarianism. It is even more congruent with anarchism, but that is largely because both of them are Utopian.</p></div><div class="reply"></div></div></li><li class="comment byuser even depth-2" id="comment-7759123" data-sort-time="1555519204"><div id="div-comment-7759123" class="comment-body"><div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><div class="comment-author vcard"> <cite class="fn"><strong>Azathoth!!</strong></cite></div> <a href="https://reason.com/2019/04/16/are-socialists-more-like-libertarians-than-wed-like-to-admit/#comment-7759123">April.17.2019 at 12:40 pm </a></div><div class="comment-content"><p><i> There are in fact strains of marxism which intersect with libertarianism</i></p><p>No, there are not.</p><p>There are strains of marxism that put on a veneer of libertarianism to ensnare the weak minded.</p><p><i> The REAL Marxism (you know, that one that no one has ever tried?) the state is supposed to fade away leaving only a voluntary collective of individuals who base their society on mutual aid. </i></p><p>No one seems to grasp what this means even though Marxists do not really hide it.</p><p>They are referring to a hive. A society where each component has and knows and keeps it&#8217;s place. It is &#8216;voluntary&#8217; only in that the capacity to exist or even think outside the framework of the society is long gone.</p><p>It is not a human society.</p></div><div class="reply"></div></div></li><li class="comment byuser odd alt depth-2" id="comment-7759193" data-sort-time="1555522142"><div id="div-comment-7759193" class="comment-body"><div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><div class="comment-author vcard"> <cite class="fn"><strong>Mike</strong></cite></div> <a href="https://reason.com/2019/04/16/are-socialists-more-like-libertarians-than-wed-like-to-admit/#comment-7759193">April.17.2019 at 1:29 pm </a></div><div class="comment-content"><p>Study Rojava. Google Murray Bookchin.</p></div><div class="reply"></div></div></li></ol></li><li class="comment byuser even thread-even depth-1 parent " id="comment-7758372" data-sort-time="1555447706"><div id="div-comment-7758372" class="comment-body"><div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><div c